Claims WHAT IS CLAIMED IS: 1. A user device application engine executed on a processor of a user device and configured to request access to secured medical information of a patient and provide a visual display of the information if authorized, the user device application engine comprising: a first application layer protocol configured to provide a user a graphical user interface which allows a user to request secured medical information of a patient; a second application layer protocol configured to call one or more application program interfaces which allows the user device to request authorization to access the secured medical information based on a trusted relationship and provide access to the secured medical data if authorized; and a third application layer protocol that, once the secured medical information is authorized and provided by the application program interfaces, displays the information to the user according to the authorization. 2. The user device of claim 1, wherein authorization to display the information is constrained according to time, such that access is restricted outside of a particular period of time. 3. The user device of claim 1, wherein authorization to display the information is constrained based on an identity associated with a user device. 4. The user device of claim 3, wherein identity associated with a user device comprises a MAC address, a CPU serial number, a globally unique identifier (GUID). 5. The user device of claim 1, wherein authorization to display the information is constrained according to satisfaction of particular constraints, and wherein the third application layer protocol is configured to restrict access to the medical information based on violation of at least one constraint. 6. The user device of claim 1, wherein the particular constraints are received with the secured medical information. 7. The user device of claim 1, wherein the third application layer protocol receives updates to the displayed information, and provides the updates, via the second application layer protocol, for outside storage. 8. A method for requesting access to secured medical information of a patient and providing a visual display of the information if authorized, the method being implemented by a user device of one or more processors, and the method comprising: providing a user a graphical user interface which allows a user to request secured medical information of a patient; calling one or more application program interfaces which allows the user device to request authorization to access the secured medical information based on a trusted relationship and providing access to the secured medical data if authorized; and once the secured medical information is authorized and provided by the application program interfaces, displaying the information to the user according to the authorization. 9. The method of claim 8, wherein authorization to display the information is constrained according to time, such that access is restricted outside of a particular period of time. 10. The method of claim 8, wherein authorization to display the information is constrained based on an identity associated with a user device. 11. The method of claim 11 , wherein identity associated with a user device comprises a MAC address, a CPU serial number, a globally unique identifier (GUID). 12. The method of claim 8, wherein authorization to display the information is constrained according to satisfaction of particular constraints, and wherein the method further comprises restricting access to the medical information based on violation of at least one constraint. 13. The method of claim 8, wherein the particular constraints are received with the secured medical information. 14. The method of claim 8, wherein the method further comprises receiving updates to the displayed information, and providing the updates, via the one or more application program interfaces, for outside storage. 15. A method of maintaining in a database secured medical records of a patient by separating the medical records into portions, wherein each portion is separately trustable such that access can be granted to only limited portions of the patient's medical records according to a specified trust relationship, the method comprising: by a system of one or more computers, maintaining, in one or more databases, health records associated with a patient, wherein the health records are divided into portions and each portion is separately trustable to one or more outside entities, wherein trust indicates that an outside entity can access each portion where trust has been established with the outside entity; receiving a request, from an outside system, for access to medical information associated with a patient, the request being received via an application-layer protocol that constrains access to the requested medical information based on a known trusted relationship and provides access for only those portions for which trust is established; and providing, via the application-layer protocol, the requested medical information. 16. The method of claim 15, further comprising: establishing connection, via the application-layer protocol, between the system and the outside system, wherein medical information provided via the application- layer protocol is encrypted. 17. The method of claim 16, wherein the established connection routes information between a user device associated with the request and the system. 18. The method of claim 16, wherein the application-layer protocol specifies constraints comprising one or more of (1) a particular identity of a user authorized to access the portions, (2) one or more user devices authorized to access received portions, (3) time information specifying a time period during which the portions can be accessed, and wherein decrypting the medical information requires satisfaction of the constraints. 19. The method of claim 18, wherein the system specifies the constraints according to a type of medical information or a user identity associated with a medical professional requesting the medical information, and wherein the outside system causes the specified constraints to be enforced by a user device which provide the request to the outside system. 20. The method of claim 19, wherein the user device executes an application configured to enforce the application layer-protocol constraints. 21. The method of claim 15, further comprising: receiving, from the outside system, updates to the requested medical information, the updates being associated with a medical professional who provided the request for access to the medical information; and updating the medical information, wherein the updates are indicated as being trusted to the medical professional. 22. The method of claim 15, wherein the health records associated with the patient are referenceable via a unique identifier associated with the patient. 23. The method of claim 22, wherein a value of the unique identifier was generated based on unique information associated with the patient. 24. The method of claim 23, further comprising: causing presentation, via a user device of the patient, of questions indicative of information usable to establish a unique identity of the patient; receiving responses to the questions; and generating, based on the responses, the unique identifier. 25. The method of claim 23, wherein generating the unique identifier comprises computing a cryptographic hash of the unique information. 26. The method of claim 22, wherein the portions of the health record do not include personally identifiable information, such that the portions are anonymous. 27. The method of claim 26, wherein personally identifiable information comprises name, social security number, phone number. 28. A system configured to maintain in a database secured medical records of a patient by separating the medical records into portions, wherein each portion is separately trustable such that access can be granted to only limited portions of the patient's medical records according to a specified trust relationship, and wherein the system comprises one or more computers configured to perform operations comprising: maintaining, in one or more databases, health records associated with a patient, wherein the health records are divided into portions and each portion is separately trustable to one or more outside entities, wherein trust indicates that an outside entity can access each portion where trust has been established with the outside entity; 

 receiving a request, from an outside system, for access to medical information associated with a patient, the request being received via an application-layer protocol that constrains access to the requested medical information based on a known trusted relationship and provides access for only those portions for which trust is established; and providing, via the application-layer protocol, the requested medical information. 29. The system of claim 28, wherein the operations further comprise: establishing connection, via the application-layer protocol, between the system and the outside system, wherein medical information provided via the application- layer protocol is encrypted. 30. The system of claim 29, wherein the established connection routes information between a user device associated with the request and the system. 31. The system of claim 29, wherein the application-layer protocol specifies constraints comprising one or more of (1) a particular identity of a user authorized to access the portions, (2) one or more user devices authorized to access received portions, (3) time information specifying a time period during which the portions can be accessed, and wherein decrypting the medical information requires satisfaction of the constraints. 32. The system of claim 31, wherein the system specifies the constraints according to a type of medical information or a user identity associated with a medical professional requesting the medical information, and wherein the outside system causes the specified constraints to be enforced by a user device which provide the request to the outside system. 33. The system of claim 32, wherein the user device executes an application configured to enforce the application layer-protocol constraints. 34. The system of claim 28, wherein the operations further comprise: receiving, from the outside system, updates to the requested medical information, the updates being associated with a medical professional who provided the request for access to the medical information; and updating the medical information, wherein the updates are indicated as being trusted to the medical professional. 35. The system of claim 28, wherein the health records associated with the patient are referenceable via a unique identifier associated with the patient. 36. The system of claim 35, wherein a value of the unique identifier was generated based on unique information associated with the patient. 37. The system of claim 36, further comprising: causing presentation, via a user device of the patient, of questions indicative of information usable to establish a unique identity of the patient; receiving responses to the questions; and generating, based on the responses, the unique identifier. 38. The system of claim 36, wherein generating the unique identifier comprises computing a cryptographic hash of the unique information. 39. The system of claim 35, wherein the portions of the health record do not include personally identifiable information, such that the portions are anonymous. 40. The system of claim 39, wherein personally identifiable information comprises name, social security number, phone number. 41. A system configured to securely service requests from applications for access to sensitive medical information and further configured to ensure constrained access to the sensitive medical information via adherence to trust relationships between patients and outside entities, the system comprising: one or more databases configured to: maintain trust information associated with a plurality of patients, the trust information indicating outside entities authorized to access medical information associated with respective patients; and one or more computer systems in communication with the databases, the computer systems configured to: respond to access requests associated with one or more applications executing on outside systems of outside entities, the access requests indicating requests for access to medical information; and determine whether trust has been given to outside entities, and provide requested access based on the determination. 42. The system of claim 41, wherein the applications provide disparate functionality. 43. The system of claim 41, wherein access is provided via an application-layer protocol, the application-layer protocol constraining access to medical information according to one or more constraints, and wherein medical information provided via the application-layer protocol is encrypted. 44. The system of claim 43, wherein the constraints comprise one or more of (1) a particular identity of a user authorized to access the medical information, (2) one or more user devices authorized to access the medical information, (3) time information specifying a time period during which the medical information can be accessed, and wherein decrypting the medical information requires satisfaction of the constraints. 45. The system of claim 43, wherein an application comprises a front-end application associated with presenting medical records of patients, and wherein the computer systems are further configured to: receive a first access request for medical information, the first access request being associated with the front-end application, and the first access request indicating an outside entity providing the request and an information indicative of a first patient; determine, based on the maintained trust information, that the outside entity is trusted by the first patient; and obtain the requested medical information. 46. The system of claim 45, wherein obtaining the requested medical information comprises: identifying one or more storage systems that store the requested medical information; and providing requests, via the application-layer protocol, for medical information to the storage systems. 47. The system of claim 46, wherein identification of the one or more storage systems is included in the first access request, or wherein the one or more databases store information identifying the storage systems. 48. The system of claim 46, wherein providing requests, via the application-layer protocol, comprises: establishing connection between a user device providing the first access request and the one or more storage systems. 49. The system of claim 41, wherein the computers systems are further configured to: analyze an access request associated with a first application and identify a type of medical information being requested; determine that the first application is authorized to present the type of medical information; and 

 provide requested access to the first application. 50. The system of claim 41, wherein the access requests are received from agents executing on user devices providing the access requests, and wherein the agents are configured to route information between the applications and the system via an application-layer protocol which constrains access to medical information provided via the application-layer protocol. 51. The system of claim 50, wherein the agents are associated with an application programming interface (API), and wherein the applications call functions of the API. 52. A method of securely servicing requests from applications for access to sensitive medical information and ensuring constrained access to the sensitive medical information via strict adherence to trust relationships between patients and outside entities, wherein the method comprises: by a system of one or more computers, maintaining trust information associated with a plurality of patients, the trust information indicating outside entities authorized to access medical information associated with respective patients responding to access requests associated with one or more applications executing on outside systems of outside entities, the access requests indicating requests for access to medical information; and determining whether trust has been given to outside entities, and providing requested access based on the determination. 53. The method of claim 52, wherein the applications provide disparate functionality. 54. The method of claim 52, wherein access is provided via an application-layer protocol, the application-layer protocol constraining access to medical information according to one or more constraints, and wherein medical information provided via the application-layer protocol is encrypted. 55. The method of claim 54, wherein the constraints comprise one or more of (1) a particular identity of a user authorized to access the medical information, (2) one or more user devices authorized to access the medical information, (3) time information specifying a time period during which the medical information can be accessed, and wherein decrypting the medical information requires satisfaction of the constraints. 56. The method of claim 54, wherein an application comprises a front-end application associated with presenting medical records of patients, and wherein the method further comprises: receiving a first access request for medical information, the first access request being associated with the front-end application, and the first access request indicating an outside entity providing the request and an information indicative of a first patient; determining, based on the maintained trust information, that the outside entity is trusted by the first patient; and obtaining the requested medical information. 57. The method of claim 56, wherein obtaining the requested medical information comprises: identifying one or more storage systems that store the requested medical information; and providing requests, via the application-layer protocol, for medical information to the storage systems. 58. The method of claim 57, wherein identification of the one or more storage systems is included in the first access request, or wherein the system stores information identifying the storage systems. 59. The method of claim 57, wherein providing requests, via the application-layer protocol, comprises: establishing connection between a user device providing the first access request and the one or more storage systems. 60. The method of claim 52, further comprising: analyzing an access request associated with a first application and identify a type of medical information being requested; determining that the first application is authorized to present the type of medical information; and providing requested access to the first application. 61. The method of claim 52, wherein the access requests are received from agents executing on user devices providing the access requests, and wherein the agents are configured to route information between the applications and the system via an application-layer protocol which constrains access to medical information provided via the application-layer protocol. 62. The method of claim 61 , wherein the agents are associated with an application programming interface (API), and wherein the applications call functions of the API. 63. The method of claim 52, wherein providing requested access for a first outside system comprises: obtaining requested medical information; and adjusting a quality characteristic associated with medical images included in the medical information, the adjustment being based on bandwidth information associated with the first outside system and/or a type of the first outside system. 64. In a system which provides protected access to sensitive medical information to trusted entities, a non-transitory computer storage media storing instructions that, 

 when executed by a system of one or more computer systems, cause the one or more computer systems to perform operations comprising: receiving information which defines a trusted relationship between a plurality of patients and outside entities, the trust information indicating outside entities authorized to access medical information associated with respective plurality of patients; maintaining in memory the trust information associated with a plurality of patients; responding to access requests associated with an application executing on at least one outside system of an outside entity, the access requests requesting access rights to medical information; and determining whether trust has been given to the outside entity, and providing an authorization indication based on the determination. 65. The non-transitory computer storage media of claim 64, wherein access is provided via an application-layer protocol, the application-layer protocol constraining access to medical information according to one or more constraints, and wherein medical information provided via the application-layer protocol is encrypted. 66. The non-transitory computer storage media of claim 64, wherein an application comprises a front-end application associated with presenting medical records of patients, and wherein the operations further comprise: receiving a first access request for medical information, the first access request being associated with the front-end application, and the first access request indicating an outside entity providing the request and an information indicative of a first patient; determining, based on the maintained trust information, that the outside entity is trusted by the first patient; and obtaining the requested medical information. 67. The non-transitory computer storage media of claim 64, wherein the access requests are received from agents executing on user devices providing the access requests, and wherein the agents are configured to route information between the applications and the system via an application-layer protocol which constrains access to medical information provided via the application-layer protocol. 68. A method of indexing network locations at which sensitive medical information is stored and responding to search queries related to the medical information, the method ensuring access to sensitive medical information is constrained according to explicit trust relationships, and the method comprising: by a system of one or more computers, receiving, from a requesting device of an outside entity, a search request indicating one or more search terms, the search request indicative of a request for medical information responsive to the search terms; accessing index information identifying network locations at which medical information is stored; analyzing the search request, and identifying one or more network locations storing responsive medical information; determining that the outside entity has been trusted to access at least a portion of the responsive medical information; and obtaining, from at least one network location, the at least a portion of the responsive medical information, and providing the obtained medical information for presentation to the requesting device via an application-layer protocol constraining access to the medical information. 69. The method of claim 68, wherein the index information indicates features of medical information and respective network locations at which the features are stored. 70. The method of claim 69, wherein the index information further indicates anonymous identifiers associated with patients. 71. The method of claim 70, wherein determining that the outside entity has been trusted comprises identifying that the outside entity is specified in trust information for one or more of the anonymous identifiers. 72. The method of claim 68, wherein the search request specifies a particular patient, and wherein the index is specific to the particular patient. 73. The method of claim 72, wherein the particular patient is associated with a DNS record, and wherein medical information associated with the particular patient is accessible via the DNS record. 74. The method of claim 68, further comprising: aggregating the information for presentation to the requesting device. 75. The method of claim 68, wherein the requesting device executes a particular front- end application, and wherein the obtained medical information is aggregated by the particular front-end application for presentation. 76. The method of claim 68, wherein obtaining the at least a portion of the responsive medical information comprises: establishing connection between the at least one network location and the requesting device; and routing, via the application-layer protocol, the at least one portion of the responsive medical information from the at least one network location to the requesting device. 77. A system configured to index network locations at which sensitive medical information is stored and respond to search queries related to the medical information, the system ensuring access to sensitive medical information is 

